{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537657"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:19:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:19:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16039"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16039"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.06,0.05,0.37,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8730"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94652"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8730"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16039"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77685"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3184"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20874"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28903"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28933"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31037"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94652"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about her thoughts. Over the past three months, she has become increasingly convinced that news presenters on television are directing their broadcasts specifically at her, and that song lyrics on the radio contain personal messages. She feels uncomfortable watching television or listening to the radio as a result. When questioned, she acknowledges that these beliefs sound unusual and that they might not be real, but she cannot shake the feeling. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She denies any substance use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious but otherwise well with vital signs within normal limits. Her speech is normal in rate and volume. Her thought form is logical and there is no evidence of perceptual disturbances. Her affect is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes these symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Delusions of reference","Overvalued ideas","Obsessional thoughts","Ideas of reference","Thought broadcasting"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case illustrates the importance of precise phenomenological assessment in psychiatry. The patient describes beliefs that neutral events have personal significance, but crucially maintains some insight that these beliefs may not be real.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdeas of reference\u003C/strong\u003E are false beliefs that neutral events or coincidences have special personal significance, but the person retains some insight into their irrationality. The patient\u0027s ability to acknowledge that these thoughts might not be real is the key distinguishing feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelusions of reference\u003C/strong\u003E are similar in content but are held with absolute conviction and fixed certainty, without any insight into their implausibility. This patient\u0027s maintained insight rules out true delusions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvervalued ideas\u003C/strong\u003E are unreasonable and sustained beliefs that are maintained with less than delusional intensity but are associated with strong affect. While this can appear similar, overvalued ideas typically relate to a specific preoccupation rather than referential thinking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObsessional thoughts\u003C/strong\u003E are intrusive, repetitive thoughts that the person recognises as their own and attempts to resist. While insight is maintained, obsessions are experienced as intrusive rather than explanatory of external events.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThought broadcasting\u003C/strong\u003E is a delusion where a person believes their thoughts are being transmitted to others or to the external world. This differs from ideas of reference where the person believes external events have personal significance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these subtle distinctions in phenomenology is crucial for accurate diagnosis and appropriate management in psychiatry. Ideas of reference may occur in isolation or as part of the prodromal phase of a developing psychotic disorder, highlighting the importance of ongoing monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ideas of reference are false beliefs that neutral events have special personal significance, but maintain some insight","Delusions of reference are fixed false beliefs about personal significance held with absolute conviction","Careful phenomenological assessment of insight and conviction is crucial in distinguishing psychotic symptoms"],"references":["Benjamin JS, Kaplan SJ. Sadock Comprehensive Textbook of Psychiatry.","Startup M, Bucci S, Langdon R. Delusions of reference: a new theoretical model. Cognitive neuropsychiatry. 2009 Mar 1;14(2):110-26."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77685"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16039"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77685"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-25T08:57:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-25T08:57:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8730"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94652"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1306"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Anxiety","synonyms":["Nervousness"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-08-21T03:03:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-13T10:06:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"met